Goals

  1. Calculate the Hill Diversity of the samples.
  2. Evaluate the rarefaction curves.
  3. Evaluate the Diversity values.
  4. Makes notes of specific samples and their seq depth.

iNEXT_color_df <- 
  color_df %>%
  # Merge with metadata
  left_join(metadata_df, by = "names") %>%
  # Merge with colors for plotting with ggiNEXT
  left_join(data.frame(breed_colors = breed_colors,
            type = names(breed_colors)),
            by = "type")

Plot diversity with ggiNEXT

ggiNEXT(iNEXT_data, type = 1, facet.var = "Order.q") + 
  facet_wrap(~Order.q, scales = "fixed") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = iNEXT_color_df$breed_colors, guide = FALSE) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = iNEXT_color_df$breed_colors, guide = FALSE) + 
  scale_shape_manual(values = base::rep(17, nsamples(raw_physeq)),
                     guide = FALSE) +
  labs(x = "Number of Sequences (Library Size)", 
       y = "Effective Number of ASVs") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none") 
## Scale for colour is already present.
## Adding another scale for colour, which will replace the existing scale.
## Scale for fill is already present.
## Adding another scale for fill, which will replace the existing scale.

Observations/Interpretations:: 1. The number of ASVs plateaus as the library size increases. 2. Sequencing depth appears to be pretty even across samples. 3. There seems to be a difference in richness (q = 0) for the different dog breeds. Labradors with diarrhea (green) have more richness in comparison to the other groups. 4. The common taxa (q = 1) and dominant taxa (q = 2) are pretty similar across the two different dog breeds. Also, a smaller library size is sufficient for these two diversity measurements.

Manually plot diversity

Rarefaction

iNEXT_manual_df <- 
  iNEXT_data$iNextEst$size_based %>%
  dplyr::rename(names = Assemblage) %>%
  # join with metadata 
  left_join(., metadata_df, by = "names") %>%
  # Add colors to data frame
  left_join(data.frame(breed_colors = breed_colors,
            type = names(breed_colors)),
            by = "type") 
# Inspect 
dim(iNEXT_manual_df)
## [1] 4920   60
# Plot it - Rarefaction Curve 
iNEXT_manual_df %>%
  # Filter out rows that are calculated by rarefaction from iNEXT
  dplyr::filter(Method == "Rarefaction") %>%
  # Now, let's draw the plot, be sure to group by the samples if using geom_line!
  ggplot(aes(x = m, y= qD, color = type, group = names)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  # Facet with the station to see the samples better 
  facet_grid(Order.q~type, scales = "free") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = breed_colors) + 
  labs(x = "Number of Sequences (Library Size)", 
       y = "Effective Number of ASVs") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  #guides(color = guide_legend(nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE)) + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, vjust = 1, hjust = 1),
        legend.title = element_blank())

Observations/Interpretation of results: 1. In general, laboradors with diarrhea have a higher richness (q = 0) in comparison to the healthy poodles/control dogs. However, both the healthy and diarrhea Labradors have a higher richness than the healthy and diarrhea Poodles. 2. The diarrhea Labradors have the highest amount of common taxa (q = 1). Diarrhea Poodles have the lowest amount of common taxa. 3. The diarrhea Labradors have the highest dominant taxa (q = 2), with the number of effective ASVs ranging from ~25-125. The number of dominant taxa among samples from Poodles are similar, ranging from about 25-75 effective ASVs. 4. It looks like breed is more of an indicator for diversity than diarrhea vs.healthy sample types.

Boxplots of Diversity

# Box plots by breed and sample type
iNEXT_manual_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = type, y = qD, fill = type, color = type)) + 
  facet_wrap(~Order.q, scales = "free") + 
  geom_jitter(size = 2.5) + 
  geom_boxplot(alpha = 0.5, outlier.shape = NA) + 
  scale_color_manual(values = breed_colors) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = breed_colors) + 
  labs(y = "Effective Number of ASVs") + 
  theme_bw() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 30, vjust = 0.8, hjust = 0.8),
        axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        legend.title = element_blank())

Observations/Interpretations: 1. There is a difference in richness between the two dog breeds. Labradors have a higher richness than Poodles. 2. Labradors have the highest range of both common and dominant taxa in comparison to both groups of Poodles.
